00:09:30.251 --> 00:09:36.161
It brought Cleopatra and Caesar yet closer together, and by the time Caesar’s reinforcements

00:09:36.201 --> 00:09:43.161
arrived, they managed to overpower Ptolemy’s forces and Cleopatra’s brother drowned in The Nile.

00:09:44.061 --> 00:09:49.261
With her brother out of the picture, the Egyptian throne was Cleopatra’s, and

00:09:49.471 --> 00:09:56.601
in 48BC, when she was 21 years old, she became de facto sole ruler of Egypt.

00:09:57.951 --> 00:10:02.371
In fact, Cleopatra did have another younger brother, who became

00:10:02.371 --> 00:10:05.591
co-ruler with his sister, as per the Ptolemaic tradition.

00:10:06.351 --> 00:10:12.851
But he only ruled in name, and when he died in mysterious circumstances, thought to

00:10:12.851 --> 00:10:18.431
have been poisoned by his sister, the throne became Cleoptra’s and Cleopatra’s alone.

00:10:19.841 --> 00:10:23.451
And by all accounts, she was an excellent ruler.

00:10:24.001 --> 00:10:28.411
She spent her days reading and responding to letters from officials, she was

00:10:28.421 --> 00:10:33.171
attentive to the needs of her subjects, she was a popular and effective queen.

00:10:34.591 --> 00:10:39.591
Shortly after she became queen, she had a child, the father now widely

00:10:39.591 --> 00:10:43.831
believed to be Caesar, although he did not publicly acknowledge the boy.

00:10:45.191 --> 00:10:52.671
For a few years, the going was good, but on the 15th of March 44 BC, something happened

00:10:52.911 --> 00:10:58.301
that really put a spanner in the works for Cleopatra, it got in the way of her plans.

00:10:59.361 --> 00:11:05.961
Caesar was assassinated, stabbed 23 times by his fellow Roman senators.

00:11:06.921 --> 00:11:12.171
What followed, at least as far as Cleopatra is concerned, was the splitting of Rome

00:11:12.341 --> 00:11:18.971
into several factions, first Caesar’s allies against his assassins, and then when the

00:11:18.971 --> 00:11:24.781
assassins were defeated, the rivalry between Caesar’s allies descended into full out war.

00:11:26.231 --> 00:11:31.301
On one side was Octavian, Caesar’s grandnephew and adopted

00:11:31.301 --> 00:11:34.491
son, who controlled much of the western Roman empire.

00:11:35.650 --> 00:11:39.981
Octavian would later become known as Augustus, but we will call

00:11:39.981 --> 00:11:43.471
him Octavian for the rest of the episode, for the sake of ease.

00:11:44.691 --> 00:11:50.401
And on the other side, initially Octavian’s ally but later his rival, was

00:11:50.401 --> 00:11:55.261
Marc Antony, Julius Caesar’s trusted lieutenant, who controlled the East.

00:11:56.721 --> 00:12:00.111
This put Cleopatra in a difficult position.

00:12:01.081 --> 00:12:08.231
Egypt was essentially a client state of Rome so she had to tread carefully and play her cards right.

00:12:09.726 --> 00:12:16.531
Marc Antony summoned Cleopatra to a meeting, which historians now believe was with the express

00:12:16.561 --> 00:12:23.311
intention of inheriting the alliance she had previously had with Julius Caesar, and perhaps more…

00:12:24.699 --> 00:12:31.289
Like Caesar before him, Marc Antony was a powerful man who had had a series of lovers,

00:12:31.779 --> 00:12:37.759
and it seems probable that he wanted to add an Egyptian queen to his list of conquests.

00:12:39.209 --> 00:12:42.609
After initially ignoring his requests, Cleopatra

00:12:42.849 --> 00:12:48.288
agreed to come, and she arrived in the summer of 41 BC.

00:12:49.727 --> 00:12:54.987
The arrival has gone down in history, with Cleopatra arriving not in

00:12:54.987 --> 00:13:00.577
a warship, but a boat filled with purple flowers and perfumed sails.

00:13:01.797 --> 00:13:06.047
And when she arrived, she refused to get off the boat,

00:13:06.527 --> 00:13:10.867
forcing the Roman general to come to her, not vice versa.

00:13:12.237 --> 00:13:17.037
Sure enough, the pair did become lovers, but historians believe

00:13:17.037 --> 00:13:20.821
this to have been a carefully calculated move on Cleopatra’s part.

00:13:22.195 --> 00:13:27.207
Marc Antony was one of if not the most powerful men in Rome after

00:13:27.207 --> 00:13:32.317
Caesar’s death, and he would be an enviable ally for the Egyptian queen.

00:13:33.870 --> 00:13:41.030
Cleopatra at this time was not even 30 years old, but had shown herself to have a well-honed

00:13:41.070 --> 00:13:47.210
understanding of politics, and how to navigate the complexities of regional politics at the time.

00:13:48.280 --> 00:13:51.500
And they were most certainly complex.

00:13:52.590 --> 00:13:59.680
She knew that having Marc Antony as her ally and lover would help secure her position, but not

00:13:59.680 --> 00:14:06.400
only that, if he became a father to her children, the pair would have an inseparable connection.

00:14:07.800 --> 00:14:12.030
They went on to have three children together, which Antony declared to

00:14:12.030 --> 00:14:15.610
be rulers of different Roman territories in the Eastern Mediterranean.

00:14:16.940 --> 00:14:24.720
What’s more, Antony divorced his wife, who just so happened to be Octavian, his main rival's sister.

00:14:25.820 --> 00:14:29.630
And if that wasn’t enough, he declared Cleopatra’s son

00:14:29.630 --> 00:14:33.730
with Caesar to be Caesar’s true heir, not Octavian.

00:14:35.050 --> 00:14:40.760
Octavian had loathed Cleopatra before all this, considering her to have seduced

00:14:40.760 --> 00:14:46.400
his brother in law and torn him away from his duties as a father and a statesman.

00:14:47.330 --> 00:14:49.720
But enough was enough.

00:14:50.530 --> 00:14:56.400
There had been a propaganda war waged by Octavian, with his supporters putting out pamphlets

00:14:56.450 --> 00:15:02.560
portraying Cleopatra as an Eastern temptress and Marc Antony as a lost and weak general.

00:15:03.773 --> 00:15:09.083
But this would develop into a military conflict that lasted almost two years.

00:15:10.303 --> 00:15:15.543
Now we could go into a lot of detail about this war, but we must skip to the end.

00:15:16.863 --> 00:15:20.683
Octavian’s forces proved victorious, and followed Cleopatra

00:15:20.683 --> 00:15:24.353
and Marc Antony back to Egypt, to where they had fled.

00:15:25.723 --> 00:15:31.693
With Octavian advancing towards Cleopatra, she barricaded herself inside her tomb and

00:15:31.963 --> 00:15:37.543
asked her servants to send a message to Marc Antony that she had committed suicide.

00:15:39.343 --> 00:15:45.403
When Marc Antony received the message he was distraught and fell on his sword, in

00:15:45.403 --> 00:15:49.943
a bid to kill himself if it would have meant living in a world without Cleopatra.

00:15:51.293 --> 00:15:56.203
But Cleopatra didn’t kill herself, at least not at that point.

00:15:57.623 --> 00:16:03.073
